    "from scipy.stats import zscore\n",
    "\n",
    "df_car_scaled=df_car_final.apply(zscore)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_car_scaled"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist\n",
    "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans\n",
    "\n",
    "clusters=range(2,10)\n",
    "Mean_Distortions=[]\n",
    "\n",
    "for k in clusters:\n",
    "    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)\n",
    "    model.fit(df_car_scaled)\n",
    "    prediction=model.predict(df_car_scaled)\n",
    "    Mean_Distortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df_car_scaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df_car_scaled.shape[0])"
   ]
  },

    "LR=LogisticRegression()\n",
    "    \n",
    "LR.fit(X_train, Y_train)\n",
    "Y_predict = LR.predict(new_data)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"The new Data Point belongs to the cluster: \", Y_predict)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

     ]

   ],
   "source": [
    "covMatrix = np.cov(X_scaled, rowvar=False)\n",
    "e_vals, e_vecs = np.linalg.eig(covMatrix)\n",
    "print('Eigenvectors \\n%s' % e_vecs)\n",
    "print('\\nEigenvalues \\n%s' % e_vals)"
   ]

     "name": "stdout",

      "Cumulative Variance Explained [ 52.45421787  69.04278236  79.68349586  86.17614977  91.33143713\n",
      "  94.2843067   96.27670728  97.51052572  98.3766432   98.89167071\n",
      "  99.24417716  99.49049637  99.68338315  99.80107333  99.89049256\n",
      "  99.96322521  99.99796993 100.        ]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "tot = sum(e_vals)\n",
    "var_exp = [(i / tot) * 100 for i in sorted(e_vals, reverse=True)]\n",
    "cum_var_exp = np.cumsum(var_exp)\n",
    "print(\"Cumulative Variance Explained\", cum_var_exp)"
   ]

    "plt.step(range(1, e_vals.size + 1), cum_var_exp,\n",

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Part 2.5 a - Explain pre-requisite/assumptions of PCA."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Assumptions in PCA\n",
    "There are some assumptions in PCA which are to be followed as they will lead to accurate functioning of this dimensionality reduction technique in ML. The assumptions in PCA are:\n",
    "\n",
    "• There must be linearity in the data set, i.e. the variables combine in a linear manner to form the dataset. The variables exhibit relationships among themselves.\n",
    "\n",
    "• PCA assumes that the principal component with high variance must be paid attention and the PCs with lower variance are \n",
    "disregarded as noise. Pearson correlation coefficient framework led to the origin of PCA, and there it was assumed first that the axes with high variance would only be turned into principal components.\n",
    "\n",
    " All variables should be accessed on the same ratio level of measurement. The most preferred norm is at least 150 observations of the sample set with a ratio measurement of 5:1.\n",
    "\n",
    "• Extreme values that deviate from other data points in any dataset, which are also called outliers, should be less. More number of outliers will represent experimental errors and will degrade your ML model/algorithm.\n",
    "\n",
    "• The feature set must be correlated and the reduced feature set after applying PCA will represent the original data set but in an effective way with fewer dimensions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Part 2.5 b - Explain advantages and limitations of PCA."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Avantages of PCA\n",
    " \n",
    "Performing a PCA can be a very good idea if we are aiming to extract the important features from our large data set. \n",
    "PCA can counteract the issues of a high-dimensional data set, and lower the dimensions of the data set\n",
    "Correlated features removed: it helps us to reduce a very large data set, this can be very useful \n",
    "if we need to run an algorithm through our data and/or visualize it. Otherwise, it would be very difficult to easily visualize all of our features.\n",
    "algorithms, this will help them to converge faster. With fewer features, the training time of the algorithms will decrease. \n",
    "Improves visualization: visualize a high-dimensional data set can be difficult. The PCA helps us to transform our data in high \n",
    "dimensions to a low dimensional data set.\n",
    "\n",
    "### limitations of PCA:\n",
    "\n",
    "PCA assumes a correlation between features. If the features (or dimensions or columns, in tabular data) are not correlated, PCA will be unable to determine principal components.\n",
    "\n",
    "PCA is sensitive to the scale of the features. If we have two features - one takes values between 0 and 1000, while the other takes values between 0 and 1. PCA will be extremely biased towards the first feature being the first principle component, regardless of the actual maximum variance within the data. it’s so important to standardize the values first.\n",
    "\n",
    "PCA is not robust against outliers.  the algorithm will be biased in datasets with strong outliers. This is why it is recommended to remove outliers before performing PCA.\n",
    "\n",
    "PCA assumes a linear relationship between features. The algorithm is not well suited to capturing non-linear relationships. That’s why it’s advised to turn non-linear features or relationships between features into linear, using the standard methods such as log transforms.\n",
    "\n",
    "Technical implementations often assume no missing values. When computing PCA using statistical software tools, they often assume that the feature set has no missing values  \n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": []
  }
